Analytic continuation 

In our analysis we will find that it is essential to extend de  beyond the
usual physical region .
Continued to the whole complex -plane, de  is an
ordinary differential equation with regular singular points at ,  and an irregular singular point
at ; and
by the general theory of differential equations, any solution of de  in the physical
region extends to a solution on the -plane.  However, this solution
may be multivalued around the singular points , .  This multivaluedness will play
a crucial role in our analysis, which is essentially concerned with the computation of the
monodromy around a particular closed contour in the -plane.  For convenience, to avoid having 
to deal with multivalued functions, we can put branch cuts in the -plane from  and  
and require that  satisfy de  everywhere except at the cuts.  In this approach the monodromy
is defined by the discontinuity across the cut.

